<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><strong>A new study found that people with obesity who lost weight had a significantly lower risk of type 2 diabetes.</strong></li><li><strong>However, when lean people attempted to lose weight, their risk of type 2 diabetes increased.</strong></li><li><strong>The researchers studied the health data of nearly 200,000 people from three prospective cohort studies conducted between 1988 and 2017.</strong></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Weight loss is much more beneficial for people with excess weight compared to individuals who are already lean, according to new research.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The&nbsp;<a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosmedicine/article?id=10.1371/journal.pmed.1004094" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">study</a>, which published in&nbsp;<em>PLOS Medicine</em>&nbsp;Tuesday, evaluated weight loss strategies and their health effects in nearly 200,000 people and found that people with obesity who lost weight had a significantly lower risk of type 2 diabetes, however, when lean people attempted to lose weight, their risk of type 2 diabetes increased.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Bariatric physicians were surprised to learn that weight loss strategies had such opposite health effects on people depending on their body mass index (BMI) at baseline.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>They suspect that underlying biological differences impact how and why people’s bodies respond differently to weight loss efforts.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“The main takeaway is that weight loss is beneficial for those who are overweight; lean individuals did not experience the same or more benefit,”&nbsp;<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.memorialcare.org/providers/mir-b-ali" target="_blank">Dr. Mir Ali</a>, a bariatric surgeon and medical director of MemorialCare Surgical Weight Loss Center at Orange Coast Medical Center in Fountain Valley, CA, told Healthline.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
